# ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# 1. PROJECT IDENTITY
# ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

You are an AI pair programmer working on AO-SOC (AI-Operated Security
Operations Center), codenamed Aegis-Link. This is a production-oriented,
AI-augmented SOC dashboard targeting security analysts. The product surface
is: what needs attention, how serious it is, why the AI thinks so, what to
do next, and overall posture.

The active feature branch is: feat/aegis-link-broker-orchestrator
Current version: 2.0.0

Never suggest patterns that work "well enough in demos." Every decision
should be defensible in a production SOC environment.


# ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# 2. MONOREPO LAYER MAP — know which layer you are in
# ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

orchestrator/   → Aegis-Link Python broker (FastAPI, port 8500)
                  Owns: alert ingestion, Ollama LLM enrichment,
                        SQLite persistence (soc_matrix.db),
                        containment/mitigate logic, SOAR stubs
                  Key file: soc_orchestrator.py
                  DB: soc_matrix.db (lives inside orchestrator/, NOT root)

backend/        → Express "UI API" (Node/JS, port 4317)
                  Owns: merging broker alerts + demo data, posture/MITRE/
                        summary computation, proxying LLM explanations
                  Never put business logic here that belongs in the broker.

frontend/       → React + TypeScript command center (Vite, port 5173)
                  Owns: Command Center, Live Alerts, Incidents, Entities,
                        Health pages
                  State: React Query for server state, local useState for UI
                  No raw fetch calls outside of dedicated service modules.

Never collapse these layers. Do not put SQLite queries in the Express layer.
Do not call the broker directly from React — always go through the backend proxy.


# ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# 3. PYTHON / ORCHESTRATOR CONVENTIONS (FastAPI)
# ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

- Python 3.11+. Use type hints on all function signatures.
- FastAPI dependency injection for DB sessions and shared clients.
- Pydantic v2 models for all request/response schemas. No raw dicts
  crossing endpoint boundaries.
- SQLite via aiosqlite or sqlite3 in thread pool — never blocking the
  event loop.
- All DB writes go through explicit transactions; roll back on exception.
- Ollama calls must be wrapped in try/except with a structured fallback
  enrichment object so the alert is never lost if the LLM is unavailable.
- soc_matrix.db must live at orchestrator/soc_matrix.db — never the repo
  root. Enforce with os.path relative to __file__.
- Logging: use Python's logging module with a structured format
  (timestamp, level, module, message). No bare print() in production paths.
- New endpoints follow the existing REST pattern:
    GET  /api/<resource>         → list
    GET  /api/<resource>/{id}    → detail
    POST /api/<resource>         → create / ingest
    POST /api/<resource>/{id}/action → trigger side effect
- Health endpoint: GET /health must always return broker status, DB
  reachability, and Ollama reachability as separate boolean fields.

SOAR (Step 6):
When wiring real SOAR execution, add an actions table to SQLite:
  id, alert_id, action_type, status (QUEUED/EXECUTING/DONE/FAILED),
  created_at, completed_at, result_json
Surface execution status back via GET /api/alerts/{id}/actions.


# ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# 4. NODE / BACKEND CONVENTIONS (Express)
# ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

- ES modules (import/export). No CommonJS require() in new files.
- All broker calls go through a single brokerClient module with a
  configurable BROKER_URL from environment. Never hardcode localhost:8500.
- Demo data is only injected when the broker is unreachable OR when
  DEMO_MODE=true is explicitly set. Always annotate demo records with
  source: "demo" so the frontend can badge them correctly.
- Error responses follow { error: string, code: string } shape.
- Middleware: request logging (morgan), JSON body parser, CORS restricted
  to FRONTEND_ORIGIN env var.
- No business logic in route handlers — extract to service functions.
- When adding MTTD/MTTR (Step 8): compute from SQLite alert timestamps
  (first_seen, mitigated_at) via broker endpoint, not hardcoded values.


# ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# 5. REACT / FRONTEND CONVENTIONS (TypeScript + Vite)
# ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

- Strict TypeScript. No `any`. If a type is truly unknown, use `unknown`
  and narrow it explicitly.
- All API calls live in src/services/. One file per resource domain
  (alertsService.ts, entitiesService.ts, postureService.ts, etc.).
- React Query (TanStack Query) for all server state. No manual fetch in
  components.
- Component files: PascalCase. Utility/hook files: camelCase.
- Keep components under 200 lines. Extract sub-components or custom hooks
  when a component grows beyond this.
- LIVE badge: any alert sourced from the broker (source === "broker") must
  display the LIVE badge. This must be enforced at the component level, not
  just the data layer.
- mockData.js: Do NOT add new mock data to this file. New features must
  source data from the backend API. Mark TODO comments when a field is
  still mock so it is easy to grep during Step 7 (entity risk).
- MITRE heatmap: driven by broker data when broker is alive. Never
  overwrite live heatmap with demo values.
- Accessibility: all interactive elements must have aria-labels. Color is
  never the sole differentiator of status (use icons + color together).

Entity Risk (Step 7):
When implementing real entity risk, derive users/hosts/IPs from
alert.affected_assets, alert.source_ip, alert.user fields in SQLite.
New broker endpoint: GET /api/entities (returns aggregated risk scores).
Remove corresponding mockData.js entries once the endpoint is live.


# ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# 6. DATA MODEL CONTRACTS
# ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Alert (canonical shape — broker owns this):
{
  id: string,
  title: string,
  severity: "CRITICAL" | "HIGH" | "MEDIUM" | "LOW",
  status: "LIVE" | "PENDING" | "CONTAINED",
  source: "broker" | "demo",
  first_seen: ISO8601 string,
  mitigated_at: ISO8601 string | null,
  mitre_tactics: string[],       // e.g. ["TA0001", "TA0003"]
  mitre_techniques: string[],    // e.g. ["T1078", "T1190"]
  affected_assets: string[],
  source_ip: string | null,
  user: string | null,
  enrichment: {
    timeline: string[],
    evidence: string[],
    soar_actions: string[],
    llm_assessment: string,
  } | null,
  containment_steps: string[],
}

When adding new fields to the alert schema, update:
  1. orchestrator/ Pydantic model
  2. backend/ merge/adapter logic
  3. frontend/ TypeScript interface in src/types/alert.ts
All three simultaneously — no partial migrations.


# ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# 7. ENVIRONMENT & CONFIGURATION
# ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

- All environment-specific values go in .env files. Never hardcode URLs,
  ports, model names, or DB paths in source code.
- Required env vars (document in .env.example):
    orchestrator: OLLAMA_MODEL, DB_PATH, BROKER_PORT
    backend:      BROKER_URL, FRONTEND_ORIGIN, DEMO_MODE, PORT
    frontend:     VITE_API_BASE_URL
- .env files are gitignored. .env.example is committed and kept current.
- soc_matrix.db is gitignored at the root level. Only
  orchestrator/soc_matrix.db is the canonical location.


# ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# 8. TESTING CONVENTIONS
# ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

- Orchestrator: pytest. Test file: orchestrator/test_broker.py.
  Cover: alert ingestion, enrichment fallback (Ollama down), containment
  state transitions, SOAR action persistence.
- Backend: Jest or Vitest. Cover broker merge logic, demo data fallback,
  posture computation.
- Frontend: Vitest + React Testing Library. Cover: LIVE badge rendering,
  MITRE heatmap data binding, alert status transitions.
- CI (Step 9): GitHub Actions pipeline runs broker tests, Node build,
  frontend build in sequence. No merge to main without green CI.

When writing tests:
- Use real SQLite in-memory (`:memory:`) for broker tests, not mocks.
- Mock Ollama at the HTTP boundary (httpx mock or pytest-httpx).
- Frontend tests mock the API layer (src/services/*), not fetch directly.


# ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# 9. SECURITY & HARDENING CONVENTIONS
# ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

- Never log raw alert payloads at INFO level — they may contain PII or
  sensitive host data. Use DEBUG level with a flag guard.
- Input validation on all broker endpoints via Pydantic. Reject unknown
  fields (model_config = ConfigDict(extra="forbid") where appropriate).
- CORS: restrict to known origins via env var. No wildcard (*) in
  production config.
- SQLite: parameterized queries only. No f-string SQL construction.
- Docker Compose (Step 9): broker and API containers must run as non-root
  users. Ollama container should have GPU passthrough only if available,
  fall back to CPU gracefully.
- Secrets: no API keys, tokens, or passwords in source or .env.example.
  Use placeholder values like YOUR_API_KEY_HERE with inline comments.


# ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
